e expected behavior. However, it appears the current setup does swallow MockitoExceptions with unsupported causes. In this context, I wonder if I can assert the message from a MockitoInitializationException for inline support without skipping dynamic coverage. But the instructions discourage early returns, even though existing tests do allow them for unsupported features.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating testing assertions**\\n\\nI’m wondering if I should use `containsExactlySameElementsAs` instead. It seems okay to use `assertThat(control.getMocks()).containsExactly(directConstruction)`, but I’m considering `containsExactlyInAnyOrder` as well. Since AssertJ utilizes `containsExactly(directConstruction)` and relies on `Objects.assertEqual`, maybe that works too due to same references. However, to be safe, I can assert size first with `assertThat(control.getMocks()).hasSize(1);` and check if the references match directly to bypass equals checks.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_lCQ7WvbvlMYvPhkfBOhYYxLQ|fc_0b2f69fb67bb8853016a05f552d4b8819e93caa9979e7ef461", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-core/5.0.0/src/test/java/org_mockito/mockito_core/StackWalkerCheckerTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "                ConstructedBase directConstruction = new ConstructedBase(\"direct\");\n                assertThat(control.getMocks()).containsExactly(directConstruction);\n\n                ConstructedSubclass subclassConstruction = new ConstructedSubclass();\n                assertThat(subclassConstruction.createdByRealConstructor()).isTrue();\n                assertThat(control.getMocks()).containsExactly(directConstruction);", "newText": "                ConstructedBase directConstruction = new ConstructedBase(\"direct\");\n                assertThat(control.getMocks()).hasSize(1);\n                assertThat(control.getMocks().get(0)).isSameAs(directConstruction);\n\n                ConstructedSubclass subclassCo